{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_figs_ver02/data/sn84026897/00516990983/1923111401/0367.xml":{"full_text":"Gifgefikm Baums-Heu\nGl\u00fcck-i Newspapers\u00e5sovtb Gsroling\nVOL. 88.\nEDGEFIELD, S. C. WEDNESDAY, NOV. 14, 1923.\nNo. 41.\nJOHNSTON LETTER.\nWon Football Game. Give a\nPounding to Orphanage.\nDeath of Mr. Milton\nLott.\nThe football team of the Johnston\nhigh school went over to Abbeville\non Friday to play the school team of\nthat place. The team from here was\naccompanied by Prof. Arnold and\nProf. Chappell, of the school besides\nothers interested. The game was an\nexciting one and while Abbeville\nteam did good playing the Johnston\nteam won by a large score. In all the\ngames that have been played, a fine\nspirit has been manifested each time\nby both the winning and the losing\nsides.\nProf. Fred L. Parker, organist at\nthe Baptist church and Mr. Avery\nBland, choir director, are arranging\na cantata for Sunday evening, De\ncember 23rd, this being \u201cThe Man\nger Prince,\u201d and will occupy an hour.\nThis beautiful musical feature will\nbe held in the Baptist church at the\nevening service, instead of the regu\nlar preaching. Members from the\nother choirs of the town will be in\nvited to join in. This beautiful can\ntata was given last year in Colum\nbia, and two of the soloists have con\nsented to again sing their parts, as\nthey will be here as Christmas guests\nof Prof. Parker.\nThe friends of Mr. 0. S. Wertz\nare glad to know that his condition\nis much improved, though he is still\nconfined to his bed.\nMisses Olin and Ray Sawyer of\nGeorgetown,. who are students of\nChicora college, Columbia, spent the\nweek-end here in the home of Miss\nClara Sawyer.\nAs a Thanksgiving remembrance,\nthe members of the New Century\nclub are sending packages of stamped\n'Piankggiving cards to the ju&Wnefe\nmen at Greenville camp for them to\nuse.\nThe members of the Baptist church\nwSl give a pounding near Thanksgiv\ning, and this will be sent to the Con\nnie Maxwell Orphanage. On next\nSunday morning, Mr. M. R. Wright,\nSunday school superintendent, will\nannounce the place for receiving the\ngifts and the receiving committee.\nMr. and Mrs. J. H. Browne have\n\u2022moved here from Georgia, and are\ndomiciled in the home of Mr. J. W.\nBrown. Mr. Browne has charge of\nthe new music store.\nMrs. Agatha White has returned\nto Greenwood after a visit in the\nhome of her aunt, Mrs. Georgia Tur\nner.\nMrs. J. Howard Payne, President\nof the Woman's Missionary Society,\nand Mrs. A. P. Lewis are in Florence\nthis week attending the State Baptist\nW. M. U. Convention as delegates.\nMrs. W. J. Hatcher, stat6 Sunbeam\nDirector is also in attendance.\nMesdames B. T. Boatwright, W.\nWallace Turner and Miss Frances\nTurner attended the Edgefield Fair\nand acted as judges in the fancy\nwork department, and other exhibits.\nThose from here to attend the\nCommunity fair atTrenton were Mr.\nP. N. Lott, Mr. and Mrs. J. W. Marsh,\nMr. and Mrs. Edwin Dasher and Miss\nZena Payne, the last two acting with\nothers as judges in the fancy work\ndepartment.\nMrs. W. C. Conley was hostess for\nthe music club on Tuesday and an\nunusually pleasant meeting was held.\nMrs. G. D. Walker and Miss Clara\nSawyer were elected delegates to the\nWestern District Conference at Bam\nberg, and several others will attend.\nMrs. J. W. Marsh had arranged a\nmost enjoyable program on \u201cThe His\ntory of Greek Music,\u201d with several\npiano and voice numbers. The hostess\nserved an elaborate salad course.\nMr. Milton Lott died at the home\nof his sister, Mrs. Mattie Beaver at\nRidge Sjring on Sunday, and the in\nterment was made here on Monday at\nthe Lott burying ground. Mr. Lott\nwas a life time resident of Johnston,\nuntil about three years ago, he went\nto Ridge Spring to live with his sis\nter, as his health was failing. He was\na devoted member of the Baptist\nchurch and Sunday school, as long as\nhe lived and he has been greatly\nmissed, and the news of his passing\nwas heard here with regret. He was\nof a friendly nature, kind, and gen\ntle, and everyone liked him.\nLumber has ibeen laid on the lot\nof Mr. Heber Ballentine and the\nerection of his dwelling will soon be\ngin.\nThe W. C. T. U. met Friday after\nnoon with Mrs. T. R. Denny, with a\nlarge attendance. There were many\ndiscussions concerning points where\nby the cause of temperance may be\npromoted, and some of the members\nwere requested to write articles for\nthe local paper to create sentiment.\nMrs. L. C. Latimer reported the ob\nservance of State Temperance day in\nthe high school. There was a short\nperiod on good citizenship and in\nteresting articles were read.\nMrs. M. T. Turner, State corres\nponding secretary, and Miss Zena\nPayne, state librarian, and Mrs. J. L.\nWalker, chapter Regent, are in\nGreenville this week attending the\nState D. A. R. conference. Following\nthe conference the convention body\nwill be carried to Tamassee, the State\nD. A. R. School, for a visit. The\nPresident General and State Regents\nof New York, North Carolina and\nGeorgia will be guests of honor.\nThe highway is now in operation\non the town\u2019s main street, and it is\nhoped that some means has at\nlast been found to remove from this\nmain thoroughfare, those ruts and\nholes that heretofore have refused\nto remain smoothed over. The town\npump, which was in the center of the\nstreet has been removed. Calhoun\nstreet, a smooth highway, offering a\ncomfortable ride from one end of the\ntown to the other, will indeed be a\nnovelty in the winter time.\nRev. A. T. Allen\u2019s Achievement\nWhen the members of the Baptist\nchurch erected their parsonage four\nor five years ago, at a cost of about\n$12,500 for the house and lot, only\n$5,1100 jtras paid an it- the time,\nleaving a debt of $7,500. Owing to\nthe financial depression of the past\nthree years, no effort has been made\nto pay off or reduce this indebted\nness. Recently the pastor, Rev. A. T.\nAllen, felt that, with the return of\nprosperity, an effort should be made\nby the church to liquidate this debt\non the parsonage. Acting upon this'\nconviction, he began a quiet person-1\nal canvass of the membership solic\niting voluntary contributions. From\nthe outset he met with much encour\nagement and persevered until he had\ncash and subscriptions amounting to\n$7,220 and made a report to that ef\nfect to the congregation Sunday\nmorning. After making the report of\nso near the goal, Mr. Allen asked for\nvoluntary contributions to the $280\nneeded to complete the $7,500. This\namount was quickly subscribed. Al\nready more than $3,000 has been\npaid in cash and the balance of the\nsubscriptions will be paid by the end\nof the year, making it possible\nthrough Mr. Allen\u2019s efforts for the\nchurch to enter the new year free\nfrom debt.\nDeath of Mrs. J. F. Bettis at\nTrenton.\nMrs. J. F. Bettis passed away in\nthe early evening of Friday at. her\nhome in Trenton. She had ibeen an in\nvalid for several months, but the im\nminence of death was not suspected,\nand her family and friends were\nshocked at her sudden passing away.\nMrs. Bettis was Miss Leila Norris\nbefore her marriage to Mr. Frank\nBettis, and came of one of South\nCarolina\u2019s best families. She was\nabout 65 years of age and had a wide\ncircle of friends.\nThe funeral services were conduct\ned at her home and continued at\nEbenezer cemetery where many\nchoice and beautiful flowers covered\nher last resting place.\nThe funeral services were conduct\ned by her pastor, Rev. A. T. Allen,\nMrs. Bettis having been a member of\nthe Baptist church at Trenton for\nmany years. Besides her husband she\nis survived by four children, Mrs.\nFrances Wolfe of Orangeburg, Miss\nes Maude Alma and Dorothy Bettis\nand one son, Mr. William Bettis of\nTrenton.\nJust received a beautiful line of\nLadies\u2019 Kid Gloves, latest colors.\nI. MUKASHY.\nRed Cross Roll Call by Parent*'\nTeacher Association. \u2018I\nEditor Edgefield Advertiser: Jj\nPermit me to use your columns tV\ncall the attention of Edgefield citf*\nzens to the seventh annual roll call ot\nthe American Red Cross which will\nbe conducted between November jjjL\nand Thanksgiving day.\nThe pulblic knows what wonderfm.i\nwork the Red Cross accomplish*^'\nhow active it was in war times an\u00ae\nwhat splendid work it has done lit\ncarrying out its peace time prograut\nThe roll call here will be conduct\ned by the Parent-Teacher Associa\ntion of the Edgefield schools. Oho\nhalf of all money raised will go i&\nthe general Red Cross fund for relief\nwork in all parts of the world and the\nother half will be used here in Edge\nfield. Of our share the Parent-Teach\ner Association will get three-fourths,\nwhich will be used in promoting :r\u00a3js\nworthy activities and the remaining\none-fourth will be kept in the local\nRed Cross treasury for charitable\npurposes. Very often the attention of\nthe writer is called -to some needy\ncase and after investigation a small\nsum is donated to relieve the distress^\nRecently the -writer had occasion to\nrender assistance to the family of an\nex-soldier who was at the point of\ndeath; bis family had no money and\nthe wife could not work because 3he\nhad to remain with her husband; the\nchildren were too small to work. A\nsmall donation went far to aid this\nfamily. During the year several simi\nlar calls have come to the Red Cross\nand we have -been able-to render as\nsistance from our small fund.\nOur citizens -have always respond\ned cheerfully -and I trust that this\nyear there will be -many who will be\nwilling to contribute a dollar or\nmore towards the support of this\nworthy organization.\nJAMES O. SHEPPARD,\nChm. E. Co., Red Cross Chapter.\nMr. Warren Bagged a Buck.\nMr. S. M. Smith, Mr. S. E. Mor\ngan, Mr. J. G. Alford and Mr. Wal\nlace Reel own an interest in a large\nhunting preserve in Charleston coun\nty 30 miles north of Charleston and\nrecently Mr. Smith, Mr.\" Alford and\nMr. Reel motored down to the pre\nserve for a deer hunt, taking Mr. F.\nM. Warren and Mr. Frank Warren,\nJr., along with them. Mr. Frank War\nren, who is now in his 80th year, was\nthe only huntsman from Edgefield\nwho killed a deer. It was great sport\nand he thoroughly enjoyed the thrill\ning experience. There are several\nlarge droves of wild turkeys on the\npieserve and as soon as the law per\nmits the Edgefield sports will have a\nhig turkey hunt.\nPresbyterian Bazaar.\nThe Woman\u2019s Auxiliary of the\nPresbyterian church will hold a ba\nzaar on December 15th. Full particu\nlars will be given later. The dinners\nwill be in charge of Mrs. L. Y. Moore\nand they invite all their friends to\ncome and get the best dinner they\never had. Please bear this in mind,\nand remember to look for the partic\nulars in a later issue.\nThe following committees have\nbeen appointed:\nLunch Committee: Mrs. L. Y.\nMoore, Mrs. J. H. Cantelou, Mrs. W.\nC. Lynch, Mrs. Ches. Wells, Mrs.\nCharlie Jones, Mrs. Pierce Ryan.\nServing Committee: Mrs. J. O.\nSheppard, Mrs. Emily Adams Mims,\nMrs. Richard Walker, Mrs. Walter\nCantelou, Mrs. W. L. Dunovant, Jr.,\nMrs. W. W. Adams, Mrs. Julian Hol\nstein.\nCoffee Committee: Miss Marie Ab\nney, Mrs. M. P. Wells, Mrs. Ramsey\nSharp, Mrs. John Anderson, Mrs. W.\nJ. Shirley.\nCake and Candy Committee: Mrs.\nN. G. Evans, Miss Lily Adams, Mrs.\nP. P. Blalock, Jr., Mrs. J. A. Town\nsend.\nTable Committee: Mrs. S. B. Hill,\nMrs. H| E. Wright ,Mrs. P. P. Bla\nlock, Sr., Mrs. Joe McClendon, Mrs.\nT. D. Barker.\nFancy Work Committee: Mrs. W.\nL. Dunovant, Mrs. Hattie Adams,\nMrs. F. M. Warren, Mrs. Wells Fow\nler, Miss June Rainsford, Miss Lois\nMims.\nMoo re-Wanna maker Wedding\nat Trenton.\nSaturday evening at 6:30 o\u2019clock,\na most auspicious event took place at\nthe lovely and spacious residence of\nMr. and Mrs. Dorian Swearingen at\nTrenton. The occasion was the mar\nriage of Miss Laurie Moore, the\ndaughter of Mrs. Swearingen to Mr.\nFrank Wannamaker of St. Matthews.\nThe friends of this happy pair had\nbeen anticipating this event for\nmonths, for the wiles of Cupid can\nnot be hid, and in this case the reali\nzation of the event was most delight\nful to those who were the fortunate\nguests.\nOn entrance a cordial hospitality\nawaited everyone, and the warmth\nand beauty of the interior left the\ncold exterior entirely out of mind.\nThose receiving at the door were\nMrs.\u00bbDorian Swearingen, Mrs. Claude\nWertz, Mrs. W. R. Swearingen and\nMrs. J. D. Mathis. As the guests en\ntered, they were conducted to the\nrear by Mrs. Wallace Wise and\nserved with fruit .punch at the gra\ncious hands of Misses Julia Wise\nand Zelime Yates. From here, a place\nof great interest was next visited, the\nroom in which the magnificent,\ntasteful and numerous gifts, a most\nvaluable assortment from many lov\ning hearts. Miss Lena Long was in\ncharge of the registration book at the\nentrance to the room. Among the\nmost striking gifts was a check for\n\u00a72,000 to the bride from Mr. and\nMrs. Skottowe Wannamaker, father\nand mother of the groom. The letter\naccompanying the check was so\nunique that it is published at the end\nof this article.\nThere were many silver and cut\nglass and hand painted china pieces,\nall above the average of excellence,\nand all the friends were enjoying the\npleasure of inspecting them when\nlovely strains of music caught the\near?' This came from the hall into\nwhich descended the stairway from\nwhich the wedding party would enter\nthe parlor.\nA group of songs and violin music\nwas given as follows:\nVocal solo, \u201cThank God for a Gar\nden,\u201d Miss Ray Swearingen, of Tren\nton.\nVocal solo, Miss Blanche Spann,\nVocal solo, \u201cCome to Me.\u201d \u201cThe\nCall of Love,\u201d Miss Blanche Spann.\nViolin selections, \u201cOne Fleeting\nHour,\u201d \u201cMeditation,\u201d by Mietzke,\n\u201cLove Sends a Little Gift of Roses,\u201d\nMiss Martha Bruce, Blackville, S. C.\nAccompaniments were played by\nMiss Leila Margaret Dickson of Man\nning, S. C.\nAt the appointed hour, Mendels\nsohn's Wedding March announced\nthat the bridal party was coming,\nand the expectant friends and rela\ntives were eager to catch the first\nglimpse of the wedding train. The\nfirst to appear was the officiating\nminister, Rev. J. E. Belk, Presby\nterian minister of Clover, S. C.,\nbrother-in-law of the groom. Mr.\nBelk entered the parlor and stood at\nI the opposite side from the entrance\nin a bower of palms and chrysanthe\nmums. Following him were five of\nthe most beautiful and attractive\nchildren which the state affords. The\nfirst^two flower girls were Annie Du\nrisoe Day, daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nRoper Day, and Katherine Beatrice\nVann, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. J.\nM. Vann, both the little girls being\nfirst cousins of the bride.\nThe next little girls were Annie\nDay, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. P. B.\nDay and Rohbie Butler Wise, daugh\nter of Mr. and Mrs. P. B. Wise.\nAll the costumes were identical,\nmade of a beautiful shade of pink\nwith many frills bound in satin, most\nbecoming and tastefully designed by\nsome artist hand. These took their\nthe entrance.\nplaces on either side of the door at\nFollowing came the ring bearer, a\nvery tiny little boy in an evening suit\nof white satin, bearing the ring. The\nlittle fellow was the son of Mr. and\nMrs. J. M. Vann, Lawrence William\nVann.\nThe attendants entered as follows,\nMiss Nida Ham, of Timmonsville and\nMr. William Wise.\nMiss Branson Price of Chappell\nHill, N. C., a cousin of the bride, with\nMr. Russell Zimmerman, of St. Mat\nthews.\nMiss Mildred Price of Chappell\nHill, with Mr. Houser Banks of St.\nMatthews.\nMiss Ella Wannamaker with Mr.\nBramwell Hill, both of St. Matthews.\nThe bride\u2019s maids were costumed\nin pink carrying magnificent bou\nquets of yellow chrysanthemums.\nThey took their position on either\nside of the parlor in a semi-circle.\nAfter these the dame of'honor en\ntered, Mrs. Marion Carrigan, of So\nciety Hill, then the maid of honor,\nMiss Allene Spivey, of Conway.\nThe groom entered from a rear\ndoor, accompanied by his best man,\nMr. Arthur Carver of Durham, N. C.\nNext the bride on the arm of her\nmother. As soon as they had reached\nthe center of the room under a beau\ntifully decorated electrolier, the\nstrains of the Bridal Chorus which\nhad commenced on the entrance of\nthe bride, became a distant echo, and\nthe officiating minister with the ring\nceremony spoke the words which\nunited these young lives.\nThe bride\u2019s mother, Mrs. Dorian\nSwearingen, wore a -black Duchess\nsatin dress draped with Spanish lace\nand a corsage bouquet of roses.\nThe bride wore white brocade\nsatin with pearls and lace and a coro\nnet of orange blossoms. Her court\ntrain was borne by her little cousin,\nWalter Stephens. The bride\u2019s bou\nquet was shower lillies of the valley\nand her beautiful face and figure\nwere never more regal and more\nlovely than on this happy occasion.\nAs soon as the congratulations\nwere extended and they were very\ncordial and sincere, Fulcher\u2019s orches\ntra continued at intervals during the\nevening to enhance the pleasure of\nthe occasion.\nThe decorations were planned hy\nMrs. Claude Wertz, an aunt of the\n'bride, and assisting here were Mrs.\nWallace Wise, Mrs. George Wise,\nMrs. Julius Vann, Mrs. P. B. Day and\nMrs. J. D. Mathis.,..--\nThe 'hall was wreathed in Southern\nsmilax and the parlor had a wealth\nof .beautiful ferns and palms ar\nranged in a circular design as a back\nground for the wedding party. The\nelectrolier was most artistic in ob\nlong covers in tulle over each light\nand from these white chrysanthe\nmums were tied with tiny white rib\nbon.\nThe dining room was arranged for\nthe repast of the wedding party, and\non a lovely centerpiece stood the\nbride\u2019s cake which looked like a white\nmarble castle as it became the most\nconspicuous and inviting part of the\ndecoration. The cake was the work\nof Mrs. Annie Wicker, whose skill in\nthis direction has already made her\nfamous. The dining room lights were\ncovered with pink tulle and festoons\nof this dainty material hung grace\nfully from the electrolier. Here the\nbridal party made merry, and contra\nry to the usual custom, they were in\nsight of all the other guests, and thus\nadded to the happiness of all the peo\nple present. Cut glass bowls filled\nwith white mints also adorned the\ntable.\nAn abundant and tempting salad\ncourse was served from the dining\nroom.\nThe bride and groom disappeared\nmomentarily from the scene of gaity\nto reappear in travelling costumes,\nand to be greeted with showers of\nrice as they descended the stairs.\nMiss Moore is a graduate of Chi\ncora college and a musician of un\nusual ability and talent. All of Tren\nton agree in sounding her praises and\nin expressing fegret at giving her up.\nShe is .beautiful personally and in\ncharacter, and popular and highly es\nteemed with all who know her.\nMr. Wannamaker is a graduate of\nTrinity College, N. C., and of a north\nern university and in business with\nhis father, Mr. Skottowe Wanna\nmaker of St. Matthews, who, besides\nbeing president of the American Cot\nton Association, has large business\nintersts.\nThe young people left on the even\ning train for Augusta whence they\ncontinued for a fortnight\u2019s stay in\nthe Land of Flowers. They will make\ntheir home in St Matthews.\nAmong the out of town guests\nwere, Mr. W. J. Crutchfield, Mrs. J.\nA. Murray, Mrs. T. H. Dreher, Mrs.\nH. C. Raysor, Miss Emma Pou Ray\nsor, Dr. and Mrs. H. A. Raysor, Mr.\nand Mrs. R. M. Salley, Miss Blanche\nAmaker, Mr. and Mrs. J. Skottowe\nWannamaker, Miss Frances Wanna\nmaker, Miss Ella Salley of St. Mat\nthews; Mr. and Mrs. J. C. Wertz, Mr.\nand Mrs. W. S. Wertz, Mrs. W. <J.\nAlbergotti, Dan and Jesse Albergot\nti and Miss Mary Albergotti of Co-\nlumibia; Mrs. J. V. Price of Chappell\nHill, N. C., and Miss Agenora Adams,\nof Fotte Motte, S. C.\nSt. Matthews,/S. C.\nNov. 2, 1923.\nMr. Mrs. Frank M. Wannamaker:.\nTrenton, South Carolina.\nDear Laurie and Frank:\nWe enclose herewith check for\n$2,000.00, which we wish you to use\nfor such purpose as you feel will best\npromote your happiness. We feel that\nyour judgment in the use of this\nmoney will be superior to ours, and it\nis for this reason we are making this'\nrequest of you, instead of making'\nthe investment ourselves.\nNo one could possibly be more in\nterested in the future happiness of\neach- of you than ourselves on ac\ncount of our love for you, and it is\nour sincere judgment, unwarped by\nthis love, that each of you have made\na wise choice, and as a result each\nwill prove a blessing to the other and\nmarried life will hold in store for you\nmuch happiness.\nIt is, of course, natural that pa\nrents should give advice; however,\nwe are giving you this advice out of\nour personal experience. These sim\nple rules have done much to promote\nan unruffled married life, full of\nsunshine and joy:\nThe very nearest approach to do\nmestic happiness on earth is in the\ncultivation on both sides of absolute\nunselfishness.\nNever iboth ibe angry at once.\nNever talk at one another, either\nalone or in company.\nNever speak loud to one another\nunless the house is on fire.\nLet each one strive to yield often-'\nest to the wishes of the other.\nLet self-denial be the daily aim\nand practice of each.\nNever find fault unless it is per\nfectly certain that a fault has been\ncommitted, and always speak loving\nly\nNever taunt with a past mistake.\nNeglect the whole world besides\nrather than one another.\nNever allow a request to be re\npeated.\nNever make a remark at the ex\npense of the other, it is a meanness.\nNever part for the day without lov\ning words to think of during absence.\nNever meet without a loving wel\ncome.\nNever let the sun go down upon\nany anger or grievance.\nNever let any fault you have com\nmitted go by until you have frankly\nconfessed it and asked forgiveness.\nNever forget the happy hours of\nearly love.\nNever sigh over what might have\nbeen, but make the best of what is.\nNever forget that marriage is or\ndained of God, and that His blessing:\nalone can make it what it should ever\nbe.\nNever be contented until you know\nyou both are walking in the narrow\nway.\nNever let your hopes stop short of\nthe eternal home.\nWith much love,\nAffectionately,\nFather and Mother Wannamaker.\nWill Locate in Atlanta.\nThe friends of Col. P. B. Mayson\nall over the county will learn with,\nregret that he has decided to leave\nEdgefield to make his home in Atlan\nta, where he will engage in the prac\ntice of law. He sold his home (resi\ndence and two and one-fifth acres)\nin South Edgefield yesterday to Mr..\nJohn W. Kemp. He has not sold his:\nfarm land or his other real estate in\nEdgefield. Col. and Mrs. iMayson wilE\nleave within a short time to make:\ntheir home in Atlanta and their de\nparture will cause genuine regret\namong their Edgefield friends.\nCome in and inspect our nice line\nof Peter\u2019s Weatherbird Shoes for\nchildren, just the kind for school\nwear.\nI. MUKASHY.","height":"25860","width":"17640"}}
